DESIGN APPROACH: 

1. The program is menu driven, by the use of switch case statements. This facilitates the 
user-friendly input taking nature of the program. 
2. Modularity is implemented by the introduction and use of the mathematical 
functionalities as functions/methods, i.e., each function has a different setup in the 
program, thereby assisting code check and enhancing appeal and code maintainability. 
3. Appropriate input types have been used, like for addition, the user is asked for multiple 
inputs, if he/she wishes to add many numbers together. 
4. For intense mathematical computation, like in trigonometric functions, Taylor series has 
been helpful in computing the said approximate results.  
5. In calculations involving multiple iterations, check variables have been implemented 
from Newton-Raphson method, to limit the looping process, while simultaneously 
conserving the approximations. 
6. Many possibilities of invalid inputs and exceptions have been handled in the code, e.g.: 
division by zero in division function. 
7. It has been tried to reach a good level of approximation, considering the use of Taylor 
series, which returns the values, not exact but approximated. Some convergence-based 
conditions and logic have been used to prevent extreme divergence of the series, 
especially at extreme end points. 
8. The use of functions built within the program has been maximised, even if they were 
needed in other methods within the program.
